<DocsLayout title="LLMs vs. LLM hosts" currentSlug="ai/hosts">
  <h1>LLMs vs. LLM hosts</h1>
  <p>
    A raw model is a function: tokens in, tokens out. It cannot open a
    file, run a shell command, or make a network call -- it only emits
    text. Everything that looks like "the AI did something on my
    computer" is actually the <strong>host</strong> around the model
    doing that work, driven by text the model produced.
  </p>
  <p>
    Claude Code, Codex, Pi, and Hermes are all hosts. They read the
    model's output, recognize "this looks like a tool call," actually
    make that call (open the file, run the command, hit the MCP server),
    and feed the result back to the model as more text. The model never
    touches your filesystem directly.
  </p>

  <h2>The browser analogy</h2>
  <p>
    Asking "does this model know MCP?" is a category error, in the same
    way "does this CPU know HTTP?" is. The CPU runs the browser; the
    browser knows HTTP. The model is the CPU-equivalent here: it runs
    inside a host, and the host is what actually speaks the protocols
    (MCP, function-calling, whatever) that let it act on the world.
  </p>

  <h2>What a model actually needs</h2>
  <p>
    Two things, and neither of them is "understanding MCP":
  </p>
  <ol>
    <li>
      <strong>Tool-calling ability</strong> -- a training property. The
      model has to reliably emit a structured call when shown a tool's
      schema. Instruct-tuned models are trained for this; a raw base
      model generally isn't.
    </li>
    <li>
      <strong>A host that bridges</strong> -- something that shows the
      model the available tools, parses its output for a call, executes
      that call for real, and returns the result as text the model can
      read.
    </li>
  </ol>
  <p>
    Tool-capable model + capable host = the combination can drive tools
    (including MCP tools, like the ones <a href="/docs/mcp-server">
    <code>cc-mcp</code></a> exposes). The model isn't "knowing" the
    protocol; the host is translating between text and protocol on its
    behalf.
  </p>

  <h2>Capability is a spectrum</h2>
  <p>
    Tool-calling reliability tracks model size and training, not a
    binary "supports MCP" flag: large instruct-tuned models handle
    multi-step tool use fairly reliably, small instruct models produce
    malformed or hallucinated calls more often, and non-instruct base
    models are effectively unusable for this without heavy scaffolding.
    The protocol always works, because it lives in the host -- whether
    the model uses it well is a separate question entirely.
  </p>
</DocsLayout>
